cyclone.name: ETA
cyclone.current_location: about 80 mi NNW of the western tip of Cuba

motion.direction: Nearly stationary (expected to drift north later)

cyclone.trajectory: Forecast to move slowly northward in the east-central Gulf of Mexico, then turn northeast toward Florida’s Big Bend late Thursday before weakening inland over the southeast United States.
cyclone.expected_landfall_location: Florida Big Bend coast (near Cedar Key–Steinhatchee area)

weather_observation.watch_coast: Tropical-storm watch limited to western Cuba (La Habana to Isle of Youth); none along Florida east coast
weather_observation.warning_coast: None issued for Florida coastline at this time
weather_observation.impacted_coast: Primary impact zone is Florida’s Gulf Coast from Naples northward to the Big Bend; secondary impacts extend across the Florida peninsula, including the east-central coast near Port Canaveral.
weather_observation.rain_fall_above_4_inch: Possible (bands from Eta could locally exceed 4 inches)
weather_observation.storm_surge_above_3_feet: Unlikely on the Atlantic side; main surge threat confined to Florida Gulf Coast
weather_observation.wind: Low chance (≤9%) of sustained tropical-storm-force winds; brief gusts 25-35 kt possible in heavier squalls late Wed–Thu.
weather_observation.storm_surge: None expected for Port Canaveral; only minor tidal departures <1 ft possible.
weather_observation.rainfall: Outer rain bands could bring 2–4 inches with isolated 4+ inches Wednesday night through Thursday.
weather_observation.other_hazards: Increased rip currents and rough surf along the Space Coast beginning mid-week.
